'''Miyake Shrine''' (みやけじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Miyake-chō, {{ill|lt=Kameoka|Q633996|qid=Q633996|1=Kameoka, Kyoto}}, {{ill|lt=Kyoto Prefecture|Q120730|qid=Q120730|1=Kyoto Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}. Its former rank under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=old shrine ranking|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

It is also called "Miyake Inari," and was formerly called "Mure Inari" and "Kusawake Inari."

=== Enshrined deities ===
* '''{{ill|qid=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama|Q3080728|qid=Q3080728|qid=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto|1=Ukanomitama}}''' (うかのみたまのみこと)<ref>Deities from precinct information board.</ref>
* '''{{ill|qid=Q10921330|lt=Wakumusubi|UNKNOWN|qid=Q10921330|lt=Wakumusubi-no-Mikoto|1=Wakumusubi}}''' (わくむすびのみこと)
* '''{{ill|lt=Ukemochi-no-Kami|Q2280323|qid=Q2280323|lt=Toyoukemochi-no-Mikoto|1=Ukemochi}}''' (とようけもちのみこと)
All three are deities related to grain.

=== History ===
[[File:Miyake-jinja (Kameoka) keidai.JPG|thumb|200px|right|Precinct<br />Honden in center, maiden on left, Toyouke Ōkami on right.]]
Founding is unknown. It is said to derive from establishment of a {{ill|lt=miyake|Q11465761|qid=Q11465761|1=Miyake}} (imperial direct estate) in this area. Though local relation is unclear, the '{{ill|lt=Nihon Shoki|Q813935|qid=Q813935|1=Nihon Shoki}}' records that in {{ill|lt=Emperor Ankan|Q241765|qid=Q241765|1=Emperor Ankan}} 2 ({{ill|lt=535|Q31019|qid=Q31019|1=535}}?) a miyake called "Soshiki" was established in Tanba<ref>'Nihon Shoki,' Emperor Ankan year 2, fifth month entry: "... established Soshiki miyake in Tanba Province." ([https://www.seisaku.bz/nihonshoki/shoki_18.html Nihon Shoki Vol.18 Emperor Ankan Chronicle] via full-text search).</ref>. It is also argued that this area was the center where the Kuwata district office stood, based on old reading of district office ({{ill|lt=gunga|Q11643230|qid=Q11643230|1=Gunga (Japan)}}) as "kōri no miyake," the broad flat terrain, and presence of this shrine suggesting miyake existence<ref>From precinct information board.</ref><ref>'Place Names of Kyoto Prefecture,' entries for Miyake village and Miyake Shrine.</ref>. Many kiln remains, thought to have produced pottery for rituals, have been found nearby<ref>[https://tanbarakuichi.sakura.ne.jp/shrine/kameoka/06.html#k059 Miyake Shrine] (Tanba shrines, personal site).</ref>.

In the mid-Heian '{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}' {{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, it is listed as "Miyake Shrine" in {{ill|lt=Kuwata District|Q11537600|qid=Q11537600|1=Kuwada district}}, {{ill|lt=Tanba Province|Q954511|qid=Q954511|1=Tanba Province}}, and ranked as a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}.

It is said to have once held a vast shrine precinct of one chō square, but shrank due to war fires in the Tenshō era and other fires including {{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|qid=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} 3 ({{ill|lt=1663|Q7577|qid=Q7577|1=1663}}). The current shrine was rebuilt in {{ill|lt=Enpō|Q1145735|qid=Q1145735|1=Enpō}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1673|Q7617|qid=Q7617|1=1673}}), and an outer covering structure was added in {{ill|lt=Genroku|Q1325001|qid=Q1325001|1=Genroku}} 11 ({{ill|lt=1698|Q7706|qid=Q7706|1=1698}}).

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 6 it was ranked {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}} under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}, and in Meiji 40 became a designated village shrine<ref name=chosa/>.

